	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1" facs="0802"/>
			<p>The<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject"> compulsory labor</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-950" type="subject">law</term> envisaged the employment of conscripts
				not liable to or desired for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1086" type="subject">military
					service</term> on work supplementary to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject"
					>military</term> effort. The virtually general mobilization has resulted in a large reservoir of such <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">labor</term> which is composed entirely or in large
				measure of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term> since their number permitted
				in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1087" type="subject">military units</term> is <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-664" type="subject">restricted</term> to 10% of the complements, and
				includes persons high in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-923" type="subject">commercial</term>, <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-937" type="subject">industrial</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-919" type="subject">professional</term> life who previously had performed
				no manual <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">labor</term> as well as former <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-886" type="subject">army officers</term> of <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jewish</term> extraction, many of high rank.</p>
			<p>They are organized in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">labor camps</term> under strict
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1076" type="subject">military</term> control, receive no pay or
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-836" type="subject">clothing</term> and live in a condition
				bordering on servitude. Most of the labor presently performed by them appears to have no connection with defense measures. [...]</p>
			<pb n="2" facs="0803"/>
			<p>Unavailing <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-984%22" type="subject">protests</term> by prominent persons
				have been made to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1003" type="subject">Prime Minister</term> and it
				is generally considered that the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-641" type="subject">persecution</term>
				of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-896" type="subject">Jews</term> will increase either at <term
					ref="#ehri_dr_nationalities_germans">German</term> instigation or in an effort to indicate <term
					ref="#ehri_dr_nationalities_hungarians">Hungarian</term> union with the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1027" type="subject">Axis</term>.</p>
